00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:22.650
&gt;&gt; Helena Zinkham: Welcome
to the Library of Congress

00:00:22.650 --> 00:00:24.920
on a wonderful fall afternoon.

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:30.270
I'm Helena Zinkham, the Director
for Collections and Services.

00:00:30.270 --> 00:00:33.790
I'm going to start today's
special program with a few remarks

00:00:33.790 --> 00:00:37.580
about the library's
amazing research resources.

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:41.970
Then Stefan Hansen from the Swedish
Embassy will introduce our speaker,

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:45.810
author and journalist,
Anders Rydell.

00:00:45.810 --> 00:00:50.610
He'll talk about his new title
"The Book Thieves: The Nazi Looting

00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:55.730
of Europe's Libraries and the Race
to Return a Literary Inheritance".

00:00:55.730 --> 00:00:58.220
We'll have time for
questions afterwards and then

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:02.190
at 4 Anders will be available
to sign copies of his book.

00:01:02.190 --> 00:01:06.460
At that time you can also
see examples of books

00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:09.390
from the Offenbach Archival Depot.

00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:11.560
The Library of Congress
had staff in Europe

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:14.550
after World War II whose
work included helping

00:01:14.550 --> 00:01:17.500
to return the stolen books.

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:22.560
The display opens with an album of
photographs showing 350 bookplates

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:26.970
that facilitated connecting
books to their former owners.

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:29.550
For publications that
lacked any indication

00:01:29.550 --> 00:01:35.850
of ownership the Jewish Cultural
Reconstruction group organized the

00:01:35.850 --> 00:01:38.970
distribution of the orphans.

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:41.770
The Library of Congress did
receive several thousand volumes

00:01:41.770 --> 00:01:47.490
from the JCR and close to 1500 are
identified in our online catalogue

00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:52.480
with the heading "Holocaust
Era Judaic Heritage Library",

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:57.790
in other words the library as a
participant in helping to identify

00:01:57.790 --> 00:02:01.430
and make sure the books
remain visible.

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:04.740
These books are cared for by the
Hebraic Section of the African

00:02:04.740 --> 00:02:08.180
and Middle Eastern Division which
has brought three special titles

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:11.860
to share with you along with a
brochure that describes them.

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:16.270
Why would the Library of
Congress take an active role

00:02:16.270 --> 00:02:19.390
in preserving international
cultural heritage?

00:02:19.390 --> 00:02:22.570
Well, our name does emphasize
that our primary duty is

00:02:22.570 --> 00:02:25.460
to the United States Congress.

00:02:25.460 --> 00:02:27.070
We answer questions for them.

00:02:27.070 --> 00:02:29.850
We undertake special
research projects

00:02:29.850 --> 00:02:32.880
but we are also the national
library of the United States,

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:37.490 position:56%
America's library and that means
that our mission is global in scope,

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:40.290
to make resources available,
to sustain

00:02:40.290 --> 00:02:42.720
and preserve a universal
collection of knowledge

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:45.630
and creativity for
future generations.

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:49.670
Just a few numbers, we're
the stewards for more

00:02:49.670 --> 00:02:57.870
than 164 million items
in 470 languages ranging

00:02:57.870 --> 00:03:02.680
from printed books, newspapers and
of course electronic databases,

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:06.930
but also manuscripts and
maps, movies and music,

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:10.410
unique photographs
and sound recordings.

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:17.880
The shelving, they tell me they've
measured it in miles, 840 miles.

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:23.210
We believe you could drive all the
way to Iowa or Wisconsin and return

00:03:23.210 --> 00:03:29.210
