00:09:13.150 --> 00:09:18.530
And it was a couple of things that
got me interested in this subject.

00:09:18.530 --> 00:09:23.720
First of all, when you
looked into the organizations

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:28.190
that organized the looting, they
didn't go after the art first,

00:09:28.190 --> 00:09:31.460
they went after the
books, especially in France

00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:34.420
and it was quite particular.

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:38.180
And another thing was
the scale of it.

00:09:38.180 --> 00:09:42.360
The looting of books,
the operation to loot,

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:49.970 position:56%
sort and transport books was much,
much larger than the looting of art.

00:09:49.970 --> 00:09:54.260
Art was, if you compare
it, a small operation.

00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:58.820
But the last and maybe
most important issue was

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:02.720
that the organizations that
were responsible for the looting

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:07.810
of cultural items, they weren't
really interested in the art.

00:10:07.810 --> 00:10:11.100
The art was sent to the big
collectors like [inaudible]

00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:15.320
and Otto Fichler [phonetic]
of course.

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:19.300
But what they were
interested in was the books

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:23.180
and not just books
but also archives.

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:25.020
And this was interesting

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:31.110
because these organizations were
also the central intellectual

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:34.360
organizations in Germany.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:38.310
It was to, first of all
Heinrich Himmler's SS

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:42.890
and Alfred Rosenberg's
organization, ERR.

00:10:42.890 --> 00:10:51.090
The common picture we have of
the book, the Nazis' relations

00:10:51.090 --> 00:10:59.630
to literature is this, the book
burnings on the 10th of May, 1933.

00:10:59.630 --> 00:11:05.400
And it's a very strong picture and
I think this image of the Nazis,

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:07.300
it's still powerful today.

00:11:07.300 --> 00:11:11.390
And it's so powerful
because we want to believe

00:11:11.390 --> 00:11:15.880
that the Nazis didn't read
books, they destroyed books

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:17.440
but the truth isn't that.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:22.130
And I think the truth is
more horrific actually.

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:30.340
The book burning in May 1933 wasn't
done immense destruction of books,

00:11:30.340 --> 00:11:34.450
actually quite few
books was destroyed.

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:42.320
Already in 1933 the Nazis started
looting books all over Germany.

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:49.770
The book burning was more a
ritual, a symbolic display

00:11:49.770 --> 00:11:55.030
where they burned books in
a kind of ritual that a lot

00:11:55.030 --> 00:11:57.500
of Germans at that time understood.

00:11:57.500 --> 00:12:01.870
This was something that
went deep in German history.

00:12:01.870 --> 00:12:06.820
A hundred years earlier German
students had burned French

00:12:06.820 --> 00:12:09.800
literature of the Napoleon Wars.

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:14.740
But the most important
reference was to Martin Luther

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:17.640
and his burning of the Papal Bull.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:21.100
Because, in the Nazi
perspective the burning

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:25.300
of the Papal Bull wasn't an
act of religious freedom,

00:12:25.300 --> 00:12:27.720
it was a nationalistic act.

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:32.750
It was the moment when the
German people freed themselves

00:12:32.750 --> 00:12:38.640
from the Catholic Church, the
power of the Catholic Church.

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:43.410
In Berlin 42,000 people
came together on this night

00:12:43.410 --> 00:12:50.500
and the speaker here was the new
Minister of Propaganda, Goebbels

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:54.040
and he said "Here, the
intellectual foundations

00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:57.970
of the November Republic
sinks to the ground.

00:12:57.970 --> 00:13:02.190
But from the debris, a new
spirit will raise triumphantly

00:13:02.190 --> 00:13:04.110
like the Phoenix".

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:08.840
The interesting part
here is the new spirit.

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:12.880
What was this new kind of spirit?

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:19.320 position:56%
The Nazis didn't distance themselves
from intellectuals, from poets,

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:23.450
from librarians, writers,
researchers,

00:13:23.450 --> 00:13:27.460
actually they recruited
them and very actively

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:34.880
because they needed them to create
the image of a new human being.

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:38.850
A couple of years later a
new institute was opened

00:13:38.850 --> 00:13:42.020
in Germany, a historical institute.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:47.330
And one of the historians here
described the role of the historian

00:13:47.330 --> 00:13:53.640 position:56%
in the new Nazi Germany and this
description I think is valuable also

00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:59.040
for other kinds of
academics, writers, poets.

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:04.480
He said "The purpose of research
is not to fight directly for power.

00:14:04.480 --> 00:14:09.400
But they can forge their weapons,
it can provide us with the shields,

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:14.070 position:56%
it can train the warriors and awaken
the fire within them, hardening them

00:14:14.070 --> 00:14:17.020
against the trials that lie ahead.

00:14:17.020 --> 00:14:21.720
The goal of this Institute is to
develop weapons for the struggle

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:27.190
of thought, one of the most
important challenges of all".

00:14:27.190 --> 00:14:31.730
The Nazis always fought to
cancel wars, the first one was

00:14:31.730 --> 00:14:40.980
on the battlefield, the battle
of soldiers, tanks, machine guns

00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:45.150
but then they fought the other
kind of war, the intellectual war,

00:14:45.150 --> 00:14:50.800
the war about ideology, the war
where the Nazis wanted to prove

00:14:50.800 --> 00:14:54.290
that the Nazi ideology
was the only true fate.

00:14:54.290 --> 00:15:01.460
And in this war, the
looting was essential.

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:15.560
During the research for this book
I used this map and this map came

00:15:15.560 --> 00:15:18.150
from Alfred Rosenberg's
organization,

00:15:18.150 --> 00:15:21.010
Einsatzstab Reichsleiter Rosenberg,

00:15:21.010 --> 00:15:24.900
one of the most important looting
organizations during the Second

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:26.200
World War.

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:31.530
And I took this map and made
a travel for almost six months

00:15:31.530 --> 00:15:36.070
and followed looters in their
footsteps, from the book burnings

00:15:36.070 --> 00:15:41.610
in Berlin to the great Jewish
libraries in Amsterdam, to Paris,

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:45.320
to Rome, to Thessaloniki and
of course Eastern Europe.

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:52.040
And the purpose of this trip was to
see what happened to the libraries

00:15:52.040 --> 00:15:56.390
that were looted, what
came back, what was lost,

00:15:56.390 --> 00:16:01.740
but also to get knowledge about
what happened to the people,

00:16:01.740 --> 00:16:03.870
the communities, the families

00:16:03.870 --> 00:16:09.010
that in some cases had built these
libraries through generations.

00:16:11.870 --> 00:16:17.020
To simplify it you can say that
the Nazis looted three kinds

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:18.770
of libraries.

00:16:18.770 --> 00:16:25.160
The first one was libraries on
socialist and communist literature.

00:16:25.160 --> 00:16:27.740
After the invasion
of the Soviet Union

00:16:27.740 --> 00:16:33.760
in 1941 the Nazis came upon
enormous amounts of libraries,

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:38.020
archives especially from
the Communist Party.

00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:41.860
But there were also targets
in Western Europe and one

00:16:41.860 --> 00:16:46.340
of the most important institutions
was the institute in Amsterdam,

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:49.970
the Institute of Social History.

00:16:49.970 --> 00:16:55.730
And this institute had been
created in the early 1930s,

00:16:55.730 --> 00:17:01.320 position:56%
as you can say a response to what
happened around Europe at that time.

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:07.060 position:56%
This institute's goal was to save an
important part of Europe's history,

00:17:07.060 --> 00:17:12.450
the worker's movements'
libraries and archives.

00:17:12.450 --> 00:17:16.690
And just in a few years they
built fantastic collections

00:17:16.690 --> 00:17:21.730
because in the 1930s it wasn't
just political refugees,

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:26.190
there were libraries and archives
on the road that had been smuggled

00:17:26.190 --> 00:17:32.600
out from the Soviet Union,
Mussolini's Italy, Franco's Spain

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:36.270 position:56%
and of course from Hitler's Germany.

00:17:36.270 --> 00:17:40.150
And one of the most important
archives had been smuggled

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:44.460
out in the early 1930s
from the Nazi Germany

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:49.310
and this small paper
here is a part of that

00:17:49.310 --> 00:17:52.740
and maybe you can read
in the bottom Karl Marx.

00:17:52.740 --> 00:17:56.580
This is the, what you
can call the first draft

00:17:56.580 --> 00:17:59.750
of the "Communist Manifesto".

00:17:59.750 --> 00:18:04.530
They had the hallmarks of
Friedrich Engels' Archive

00:18:04.530 --> 00:18:10.550
and this archive was kind of
a Holy Grail for the Nazis

00:18:10.550 --> 00:18:16.080
because the Communists, the
Socialists, the Bolsheviks were one

00:18:16.080 --> 00:18:18.980
of the Nazis' main enemies.

00:18:18.980 --> 00:18:21.730
But wasn't just the
political enemies,

00:18:21.730 --> 00:18:26.340
because there were strong social
influences in the Nazi Party.

00:18:26.340 --> 00:18:30.480
Early on, there were parts of
the Nazi movement that wanted

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:33.700
to nationalize the large
companies for example.

00:18:33.700 --> 00:18:40.520
You can say that the Communists and
especially the Bolsheviks weren't

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:44.570
so much a political enemy,
they were something more.

00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:50.890
They were part of what you call
the Bolshevik Communist conspiracy.

