was connected to the Holocaust.

00:35:53.850 --> 00:36:04.180
At this institute Nazi researchers
studied Jewish history, language,

00:36:04.180 --> 00:36:07.340
culture and to this institute some

00:36:07.340 --> 00:36:12.240
of the most important Jewish
collections were sent.

00:36:12.240 --> 00:36:19.040
Why was it so important to study
Jewish history and culture?

00:36:19.040 --> 00:36:23.380
When Alfred Rosenberg
inaugurated the institute he said

00:36:23.380 --> 00:36:29.680
that it may come a day
when our grandchildren grow

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:33.170
up in a world freed from Jews

00:36:33.170 --> 00:36:38.120
where maybe they can't really
understand the threat the Jews

00:36:38.120 --> 00:36:42.570
proposed for our time,
therefore the goal

00:36:42.570 --> 00:36:46.770 position:56%
of this institute is to remind them.

00:36:46.770 --> 00:36:51.100
And he said the human
memory is very short.

00:36:51.100 --> 00:36:54.870
What Alfred Rosenberg was
afraid of was of course,

00:36:54.870 --> 00:37:01.250
that future generations in a world
without Jews, would judge them

00:37:01.250 --> 00:37:08.680
for their actions and that they
wouldn't understand why they had

00:37:13.750 --> 00:37:15.570
to do this horrible thing.

00:37:15.570 --> 00:37:18.820
I think one of the most important
lessons about the looting is

00:37:18.820 --> 00:37:25.090 position:56%
that it wasn't done to eradicate the
history or culture of their enemies

00:37:25.090 --> 00:37:28.270
but to take control over it.

00:37:28.270 --> 00:37:34.780
Because, if you own your enemies'
libraries, if you own their books,

00:37:34.780 --> 00:37:40.340
their archives, you also have
the power to write their history,

00:37:40.340 --> 00:37:43.530
that was the main goal
with the looting.

00:37:43.530 --> 00:37:49.710
As Alon Confino puts it in his
book "A World Without Jews",

00:37:49.710 --> 00:37:51.070
"Remembering the Jews

00:37:51.070 --> 00:37:55.950
after a victorious war would
have been important precisely

00:37:55.950 --> 00:38:00.920
because total liquidation of the
Jews could not have been achieved

00:38:00.920 --> 00:38:06.210
by physical annihilation alone,
it required as well the overcoming

00:38:06.210 --> 00:38:10.180
of Jewish history,
memory and history.

00:38:10.180 --> 00:38:13.870
The Nazis struggle against
the Jews was never principally

00:38:13.870 --> 00:38:18.180
about the political and
the economical influence.

00:38:18.180 --> 00:38:23.590
It was about their identity waged
by the means of Nazi appropriation

00:38:23.590 --> 00:38:27.940
of Jewish history,
memory and books".

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:32.780
The Nazis wanted a future
with generations to remember,

00:38:32.780 --> 00:38:36.540
remember what happened
but only by taking control

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:39.490
of Jewish history and culture.

00:38:39.490 --> 00:38:43.990
Could the Nazis also take control
over the memory of the Jews

00:38:43.990 --> 00:38:48.760
in a world where they
didn't exist anymore?

00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:55.150 position:56%
In the Nazi world view the Jew would
become the devil and incarnation

00:38:55.150 --> 00:39:01.520
of evil that would scare the
children long after they were dead.

00:39:01.520 --> 00:39:07.370 position:56%
After the war these books, libraries
and archives were found all

00:39:07.370 --> 00:39:13.350
over Europe and their fate
was very different depending

00:39:13.350 --> 00:39:19.080
on who found them and
where they were found.

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:27.110
Early in 1945 Stalin in a secret
operation created so-called Soviet

00:39:27.110 --> 00:39:29.760
Trophy Brigades.

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:34.820
And the goal of these brigades
was to take as much as they could

00:39:34.820 --> 00:39:39.060
from Germany but also
from Central Europe.

00:39:39.060 --> 00:39:44.990
And the Soviet Trophy Brigades
took over 11 million books

00:39:44.990 --> 00:39:48.520
to the Soviet Union that
were looted and many,

00:39:48.520 --> 00:39:54.480
many more from German
libraries and universities.

00:39:55.810 --> 00:40:01.330
Many of these collections were
scattered, separated and most

00:40:01.330 --> 00:40:04.530
of these books have
never been returned.

00:40:04.530 --> 00:40:11.600
It was a different procedure in the
West where the monuments men sorted

00:40:11.600 --> 00:40:19.640
and succeeded in returning millions
of books at the Offenbach Depot,

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:24.380
a sorting center outside
of Frankfurt, among them,

00:40:24.380 --> 00:40:28.340
many of the books that had been
found at the Frankfurt Institute,

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:33.070
but there was still a problem.

00:40:33.070 --> 00:40:37.960
Even if you could find out
who owned a book there wasn't,

00:40:37.960 --> 00:40:42.560
it was far from certain
that there was still someone

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:45.120
to return the book to.

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:48.550
As one of the monuments
men later wrote

00:40:48.550 --> 00:40:52.350
"In the sorting room I would
come upon a box of books

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:56.850
which the sorters had brought
together like scattered sheep

00:40:56.850 --> 00:41:02.160
into one fold - books from a
library which once had been

00:41:02.160 --> 00:41:07.590
in some distant town in
Poland or an extinct Yeshiva.

00:41:07.590 --> 00:41:11.940
There was something sad and
mournful about these volumes

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:17.860 position:56%
as they were whispering a tale of
yearning and hope since obliterated.

00:41:17.860 --> 00:41:22.300
I would find myself straightening
out these books and arranging them

00:41:22.300 --> 00:41:26.010
in the boxes with a
personal sense of tenderness

00:41:26.010 --> 00:41:29.170
as if they had belonged
to someone dear to me,

00:41:29.170 --> 00:41:31.090
someone recently deceased".

00:41:31.090 --> 00:41:40.760
Many of these books were later
sent out to Jewish communities,

00:41:40.760 --> 00:41:44.740
to institutions around the world.

00:41:44.740 --> 00:41:51.450
But still despite both the
efforts to loot books after war

00:41:51.450 --> 00:41:57.280
and return them, there were
millions and millions of books left

00:41:57.280 --> 00:42:01.380
in German libraries and in
other European libraries.

00:42:01.380 --> 00:42:08.080
And, when I travelled around
Europe I found them everywhere.

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:13.740
In my book I especially
focused on a library in Berlin,

00:42:13.740 --> 00:42:17.310
the Zentral und Landesbibliothek.

00:42:17.310 --> 00:42:20.370
Today there are estimates
that there could be

00:42:20.370 --> 00:42:26.790
around a quarter million looted
books just in this library.

00:42:32.650 --> 00:42:38.260
And most of the looted books at
this library aren't valuable books,

00:42:38.260 --> 00:42:43.610
aren't important books, it's
just books that belonged

00:42:43.610 --> 00:42:48.670
to ordinary people because the
Nazis didn't just loot books

00:42:48.670 --> 00:42:54.300 position:56%
from important libraries and
archives, they looted from everyone.

00:42:54.300 --> 00:43:01.180
In 1942 Alfred Rosenberg
initiated the so-called M-Aktion,

00:43:01.180 --> 00:43:02.920
Mobel Aktion.

00:43:02.920 --> 00:43:09.500
It was an operation where 70,000
homes in France, The Netherlands

00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:14.030
and Belgium were emptied
of everything, furniture,

00:43:14.030 --> 00:43:18.130
toys [inaudible] and
of course books.

00:43:18.130 --> 00:43:21.030
And, hundreds and hundreds
of thousands

00:43:21.030 --> 00:43:23.460
of these books were
brought to Germany

00:43:23.460 --> 00:43:27.410
and often sold to German libraries.

00:43:31.230 --> 00:43:35.520
And the library in Berlin,

00:43:35.520 --> 00:43:42.910
they don't have big collections
either they have one or a few books

00:43:42.910 --> 00:43:49.010
from thousands and
thousands of small libraries.

00:43:49.010 --> 00:43:52.600 position:56%
And today a small team of
librarians sort through a collection

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:58.430
of 7 million books by hand and they
have worked for almost a decade.

00:43:58.430 --> 00:44:04.100
And they have returned 600
books, so you understand

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:10.670
that this is something that's
going to go on for decades

00:44:10.670 --> 00:44:13.050
or maybe for generations.

00:44:13.050 --> 00:44:18.210
One question I asked when
I came to this library was,

00:44:18.210 --> 00:44:21.730
why hasn't this been
brought up earlier?

00:44:21.730 --> 00:44:28.660
The libraries started doing
this research ten years ago.

00:44:28.660 --> 00:44:34.210
And one important reason was
that it wasn't librarians

00:44:34.210 --> 00:44:40.530
that were held responsible
for the crimes after the war.

00:44:40.530 --> 00:44:47.380
The same librarians ought to be,
that had taken part of the looting,

00:44:47.380 --> 00:44:52.160 position:56%
held that position after the war and
often tried to hide this history.

00:44:52.160 --> 00:44:59.510
They hid the traces and today you
can find a lot of books that look

00:44:59.510 --> 00:45:05.600
like this, when you have tried
to destroy Jewish bookplates.

00:45:05.600 --> 00:45:10.390
In other cases you have, they
have tried to falsify catalogues.

00:45:10.390 --> 00:45:13.740
During the war there wasn't
a problem to put the 'J'

00:45:13.740 --> 00:45:16.030
in the books for Jewish books.

00:45:16.030 --> 00:45:21.720 position:56%
It didn't look as good after the war
so they tried to make it a donation

00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:26.610
from someone with 'J', Jiako
[phonetic] or something.

00:45:26.610 --> 00:45:31.680
And, you can also ask, why is it
important to return these books?

00:45:31.680 --> 00:45:37.980
They aren't valuable and ten
years' of work for 600 books,

00:45:37.980 --> 00:45:46.200
and it's 600 books to around,
a little more than 100 people.

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:49.830
And in my book I wanted to do,
follow one of these single books

00:45:49.830 --> 00:45:52.720
because I understood that every one

00:45:52.720 --> 00:45:55.360
of these books also
carried a history.

00:45:55.360 --> 00:46:01.090
And, as one of the librarians
here said it's often a history

00:46:01.090 --> 00:46:03.840
that ends at Auschwitz.

00:46:03.840 --> 00:46:11.410
And I came in contact with this
book, and this book was a book

00:46:11.410 --> 00:46:16.510
that belonged to just an
ordinary German Jewish man

00:46:16.510 --> 00:46:21.000 position:56%
that was called Richjart [phonetic]
Kobrak and he was a lawyer in Berlin

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:25.150
and lived there with his
wife and three children.

00:46:25.150 --> 00:46:29.200
And he didn't really
have a Jewish identity.

00:46:29.200 --> 00:46:35.360
The family was Christian and he
had been awarded the Iron Cross

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:38.030
of the [inaudible] in
the First World War.

00:46:38.030 --> 00:46:44.000
So, when Hitler came to power
he refused to leave Germany.

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:49.100
He meant that he was more German
than that Austrian Hitler.

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:53.810
And that was a mistake of course.

00:46:53.810 --> 00:46:56.960
After the Kristallnacht
they understood

00:46:56.960 --> 00:47:00.580
that they'd found a big mistake.

00:47:00.580 --> 00:47:05.050
And they tried to get out
and they succeeded sending

00:47:05.050 --> 00:47:08.490
out the three children
but Richjart Kobrak

00:47:08.490 --> 00:47:12.560
and his wife died in Auschwitz.

00:47:12.560 --> 00:47:20.080
I took this book and followed
it to Richjart Kobrak's son,

00:47:20.080 --> 00:47:22.230
Helmet [phonetic] Kobrak.

00:47:22.230 --> 00:47:31.520
Helmet Kobrak was 15 years old when
he came to Great Britain in 1939.

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:37.250
The problem was that the British
didn't see him as a Jewish refugee

00:47:37.250 --> 00:47:41.030
so they arrested him and
deported him on a ship

00:47:41.030 --> 00:47:44.250
with prisoners to Australia.

00:47:44.250 --> 00:47:50.860
It took almost 10 years for him to
get back to his sisters in England.

00:47:50.860 --> 00:47:56.750
I took this book and returned it to
Helmet's daughter, a woman living

00:47:56.750 --> 00:48:00.670
in a small village
outside Birmingham.

00:48:00.670 --> 00:48:05.350
And this book was the first
thing the family ever got back

00:48:05.350 --> 00:48:08.050
from Richjart Kobrak.

00:48:08.050 --> 00:48:12.470
This was a man that had
left almost nothing.

00:48:12.470 --> 00:48:14.030
They didn't have any photographs.

00:48:14.030 --> 00:48:17.640
They didn't have a grave of course

00:48:17.640 --> 00:48:25.290
and in some ways this book was the
only proof that he ever existed.

00:48:25.290 --> 00:48:29.420
I think this tells something
important about restitution

00:48:29.420 --> 00:48:34.130
because with the focus on art,
restitution has been a lot

00:48:34.130 --> 00:48:38.180
about the value of
artworks and money.

00:48:38.180 --> 00:48:43.130
But I mean the moral
center, the moral quest

00:48:43.130 --> 00:48:49.650
of the restitution isn't economical
compensation, that's important

00:48:49.650 --> 00:48:52.370
but it's not the moral center.

00:48:52.370 --> 00:48:53.670
It's to get back.

00:48:53.670 --> 00:48:55.920
It's to give back something
of the lives

00:48:55.920 --> 00:48:58.250
and worlds that were destroyed.

00:48:58.250 --> 00:49:05.380
To return a book to Thessaloniki
is a way to return a small part

00:49:05.380 --> 00:49:09.120
of a history that isn't
here anymore.

00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:15.960 position:56%
And this book here, it's practically
worthless, you can buy it

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:20.620
for a dollar at the bookseller

00:49:20.620 --> 00:49:25.440
but for this family it's the
most important book in the world.

